project:
Code to set the locations of each object. 
If you have objects named Earth and Moon you could write:
Moon.X= Earth.X + 50*cos(time/27.3*360)
Moon.Y= Earth.Y + 50*sin(time/27.3*360)

Hit the \[code help] to see the full guide.

if time = 0
 Sun.x = 0
 Sun.y = 0
Earth.X = Sun.X + 300*cos(time/365*360)
Earth.Y = Sun.Y + 300*sin(time/365*360)
Moon.X = Earth.X + 50*cos(time/27.3*360)
Moon.Y = Earth.Y + 50*sin(time/27.3*360)
print "Earth X: " & Earth.X & newline & "Earth Y: " & Earth.Y

In the position code box you can use a basic simple programming language to move the objects. The objects must have names. Names of objects are case sensitive. [b]All the examples below assume there are objects named [font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]Sun[/font], [font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]Earth[/font], and [font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]Moon[/font].[/b][size=5]

[/size]To change the x or y location of an object you can write a line like:
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]    Sun.X = 10[/font]
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]    Earth.Y = Sun.Y - 10[/font][size=5]

[/size]Trig functions in degrees are supported:
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]    Earth.X = Sun.X + 100*cos(time*360)[/font]
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]    Earth.Y = Sun.Y + 100*sin(time*360)[/font][size=5]

[/size]Custom Variables are always followed by [font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]()[/font]. They are case sensative. Both global variables and object variables are supported. For example:
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]    AUDistance() = 149597871[/font]
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]    Earth.V() = 364280112/(AUDistance())^0.5[/font]
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]    Moon.velocity() = Earth.V()*2 -3[/font][size=5]

[/size][font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]Time[/font] and [font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]dt[/font] are special variables. [font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]Time[/font] is the running time for the simulation. [font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]Dt[/font] is the time it takes for the simulation to update ~1/60 seconds. You can use them like this:
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]    Earth.Y = 20 + 10*time + 1/2*-9.8*time^2[/font]
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]    Moon.X = Moon.X + 100*dt[/font][size=5]

[/size][font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]If[/font] statements are supported using [/size][font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]=[/font], [/size][font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]<>[/font], [/size][font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]<[]=[/font], [/size][font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]<[/font], [/size][font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]>[]=[/font], and [/size][font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]>[/font]. 
They use indentation level with one space (" ") per level of if:
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]    if time > 1[/font]
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]     Earth.VelocityDirection() = -1[/font]
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]     if time <[]= 10[/font]
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]      Moon.X = Earth.X[/font]
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]      Moon.Y = Earth.Y + 10[/font]
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]     Earth.Y = -10[/font][size=5]

[/size]Comments start with [font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]//[/font].
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]    if Earth.X > Moon.X - 18 // Check to see if the Earth hits the moon[/font]
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]     Earth.X = Earth.X - 100*dt //if it does, move backwards[/font][size=5]

[/size]Show text with [font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]print()[/font]. Join with [font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]&[/font]. newline to return.
[font=CascadiaMono-Semilight]    print("Earth X: " & Earth.X*10 & newline & "Earth Y: " & Earth.Y*10)[/font]
